],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUnconjugated bilirubin is \u003Cstrong\u003Ebound to albumin\u003C/strong\u003E in circulation because of its hydrophobic properties. This binding is essential for transport to hepatocytes where conjugation occurs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarried within erythrocytes\u003C/strong\u003E - Once bilirubin is formed from haem breakdown, it remains in the plasma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDissolved in plasma water\u003C/strong\u003E - The hydrophobic nature of unconjugated bilirubin prevents direct dissolution in plasma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBound to alpha-globulins\u003C/strong\u003E - While globulins transport various substances, they do not significantly bind bilirubin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransported by lipoproteins\u003C/strong\u003E - Lipoproteins primarily transport cholesterol and triglycerides\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin binding prevents unconjugated bilirubin from entering tissues inappropriately. This is particularly important for protecting the brain by preventing bilirubin from crossing the blood-brain barrier.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Unconjugated bilirubin requires protein binding for blood transport due to its lipophilic nature","Albumin is the primary carrier protein for unconjugated bilirubin in circulation","The albumin-bilirubin complex prevents bilirubin from crossing the blood-brain barrier"],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61251"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17322"}},"stemMedia"